    evidence: "MOST WIDELY USED xenograft worldwide. Per Piattelli 1999: particles visible at 4 YEARS with ongoing osteoclastic resorption — very slow to non-resorbable. This is both the advantage (volume stability) and limitation (graft never fully replaced by host bone). Per Kangwannarongkul 2018: superior bone volume vs DFDBA at 1 and 3 months with upregulation of osteogenic genes (Runx2, ALP, OPN, OCN). Available as Bio-Oss granules (0.25–1mm or 1–2mm) and Bio-Oss Collagen (granules + 10% collagen for handling).\n\nPer Piattelli 1999 (Int J Oral Maxillofac Implants): 20-case long-term histologic study showed Bio-Oss particles at 4 years with active osteoclastic resorption — the graft integrates but resorbs VERY slowly. Per Kangwannarongkul 2018: micro-CT showed Bio-Oss produced superior bone volume vs DFDBA with significant upregulation of osteogenic markers. Per Korzinskas 2026 (In Vivo): Bio-Oss's high-temperature sintering induces higher anti-inflammatory CD163+ macrophage proportion vs other xenografts — favorable immune response. Per Froum 2006: in paired sinus comparison, Bio-Oss showed 12.44% vital bone + 33.0% residual graft at 26–32 weeks vs Puros 28.25% vital + 7.65% residual. Bio-Oss trades SPEED of remodeling for VOLUME stability. Per Miron 2024: optimal strategy is 20–30% autograft mixed with 70–80% Bio-Oss — combines osteogenic biology with dimensional stability. Bio-Oss Collagen (granules + 10% porcine collagen) improves handling and defect adaptation.",
